{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_5","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md && printf '\\\\n---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md && printf '\\\\n---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json && printf '\\\\n---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md\"","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_5","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md && printf '\\\\n---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md && printf '\\\\n---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json && printf '\\\\n---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Existing App UX Intake\n\n## Source Policy\n- I used only repository files, run context artifacts, local tests, scripts, and local onboarding/wake/app/shell code.\n- No external browsing, competitor scraping, or additional proprietary assets were used.\n- No secrets, credentials, tokens, cookies, private keys, session values, or environment variables were recorded.\n- This intake is scoped to UX observation only and does not assume any behavioral or product-policy changes.\n\n## Source List\n- .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json\n- .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json\n- apps/waketask-ios/README.md\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/AppRootView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/LaunchRouter.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/MainTabView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/OnboardingContainerView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/OnboardingPage.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/OnboardingPageView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/HomeView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/HomeContent.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/HomeViewModel.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/QuickActionCard.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Wake/WakeDashboardView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Wake/WakeFlowViewModel.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/ProfileView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/ProfileViewModel.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Profile/ProfileHeader.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Profile/ProfileAccountInfoSection.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Profile/ProfileQuickActionsSection.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Profile/ProfileAboutSection.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Profile/ProfileDangerZoneSection.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Profile/EditProfileSheet.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/SignInView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/EmailLoginView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/EmailSignUpView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/ForgotPasswordView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Auth/EmailSignUpFormFields.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/Auth/EmailSignUpViewModel.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/LegalDocumentView.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/FeatureCard.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/AppShell/SubscriptionStatusCard.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Localization/Resources/en.lproj/Localizable.strings\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Localization/Sources/Localization/L10n+Wake.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Localization/Sources/Localization/L10n+Onboarding.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Localization/Sources/Localization/L10n+Common.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Localization/Sources/Localization/L10n+Auth.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Localization/Sources/Localization/L10n+A11y.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Core/Sources/Core/WakeTask/WakeTaskModels.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Core/Sources/Core/WakeTask/WakeContractEvaluator.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Core/Sources/Core/WakeTask/WakeTaskProtocols.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/Packages/Core/Sources/Core/WakeTask/DefaultWakeMissionRotationEngine.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProTests/LaunchRouterTests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProTests/HomeViewModelTests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProTests/HomeContentTests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProTests/WakeTask/WakeFlowViewModelTests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProTests/AppShellSnapshotTests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProUITests/IntegrationWakeExploratoryUITests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProUITests/AuthFlowUITests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProUITests/ChatFlowUITests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/SwiftAIBoilerplateProUITests/PaywallFlowUITests.swift\n- apps/waketask-ios/scripts/qa/appium-exploratory-tapper.sh\n- prompts/iphone-app-factory/ux-existing-app-intake.md\n- .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json (if present)\n\n## Current App Purpose\nThe app is a wake-up assistant with mission-driven habit support. It guides users from first launch through onboarding, authentication, and an initial home/workspace dashboard where wake tasks are created, run, and reviewed. A chat/history lane is linked into the flow and the app includes support and account/profile sections.\n\n## Current User Flow\n1. Launch route starts at `LaunchRouter`.\n2. If onboarding is incomplete, the app presents a 3-page onboarding modal.\n3. Auth gate appears next with social plus email entry points.\n4. On sign-in success, user lands in root shell with tabs.\n5. Main tabs: Home, Runs, Profile.\n6. Home exposes quick actions and feature/summary cards.\n7. Runs opens wake dashboard and task execution state.\n8. Profile provides account management, help/settings links, legal links, and destructive actions.\n9. Tests/UX scripts include flows for auth, wake run exploration, chat, and paywall.\n\n## Current Screens And States\n- Onboarding: three slides with paging and button flow, skip behavior tied to page state.\n- Sign in and auth: social sign-in + email login/sign-up + forgot-password path.\n- Home: card-based quick actions and feed-like layout via `HomeContent`.\n- Home states: normal actions, empty recent section, and wake onboarding handoff to primary task creation.\n- Runs/Wake dashboard: list/selector, active flow, completion UI, wake-check and escalation controls.\n- Wake flow details: mission state progression, active timer behavior, completion states, and wake-check interactions.\n- Profile: user header/account details, quick account actions, settings-like legal/about/help actions, danger-zone actions.\n- Error/loading states: present in model and tests but not always fully surfaced in the UI.\n- Missing/weakly observed visual evidence: no screenshot pack or simulator captures were found in this run workspace.\n\n## Current App Weaknesses\n- Navigation: onboarding-first gating is rigid; “Runs” label is weakly descriptive versus visible behavior; deep actions are spread across multiple taps; no visible bottom-anchored persistent onboarding summary.\n- Hierarchy: task-first purpose is hidden under generic cards and tab labels; profile legal/help actions compete with operational actions.\n- Copy: strong product positioning onboarding exists, but many production strings are utilitarian or inconsistent across wake states and some copy appears generic template-style.\n- Interaction states: weak empty/loading feedback in some flows; debug-only sign-in path risks production ambiguity; many transitions rely on implicit default states.\n- Accessibility: several controls include accessibility labels, but coverage is partial in profile and dashboard controls.\n- Emotional tone: mostly supportive on goals but can be abrupt in state transitions; there is little emotional continuity between success, failure, and recovery states.\n\n## Protected Existing Systems\n- auth: keep auth providers, entry points, and auth flow wiring out of scope until later ADR approval.\n- payments: keep paywall/subscription and purchase orchestration out of scope until later ADR approval.\n- storage: keep persistence and user data handling out of scope until later ADR approval.\n- networking: keep API/client wiring out of scope until later ADR approval.\n- localization: keep translation keys/strings architecture out of scope until later ADR approval.\n- settings: keep broader settings architecture out of scope until later ADR approval.\n- design system: keep base component architecture out of scope until later ADR approval.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n- Keep the three-stage onboarding + auth-first flow shape because it already produces predictable first-run progression.\n- Keep tab-based task/home/profile separation as a stable mental model.\n- Keep card-driven quick actions and concise goal framing on home.\n- Keep explicit wake mission progression logic and clear active-state signaling.\n- Keep modular view-model/state ownership separation between Home, Wake, and Profile.\n- Keep local accessibility labeling where available and extend rather than replace.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n- Do not copy hidden or weak debug-only authentication flows.\n- Do not copy placeholder or non-functional links in profile/legal/help as-is.\n- Do not copy under-specified interaction handling where loading, disabled, and failure states are not visible.\n- Do not copy external competitor or App Store patterns without sourcing current evidence and approvals.\n- Do not copy copy that feels generic or emotionally inconsistent with intended journey.\n- Do not copy weak labeling gaps where controls are not fully announced for accessibility.\n\n## Open Questions\n- Which user segments must we optimize for first: new user wake completion vs repeat users with skipped onboarding?\n- Should “Runs” be renamed and restructured for discoverability without disrupting existing telemetry?\n- What emotional voice do we want for failure and fallback states in wake sessions?\n- What level of accessibility depth is required before release: label parity only, or full dynamic announcements and rotor/semantic ordering?\n- Which interaction states must be mandatory for each action path before UX validation (especially paywall-adjacent and error handling)?\n\n---\n# Design Opportunity Synthesis\n\n## Source Policy\n\n- Source scope is limited to repository evidence already present in this run: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`, and baseline capture command outputs.\n- Missing research artifacts from fanout branches were not available in the workspace despite successful stage completion markers.\n- External research fetches were constrained; environment preflight indicated failures for `https://apps.apple.com/`, `https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/`, `https://api.mobbin.com/mcp`, `https://pageflows.com/`, and `https://www.reddit.com/`.\n- Where direct evidence is absent, observations are marked as inference and constrained to interaction-level principles only.\n- No secrets, credentials, private keys, environment values, or proprietary screenshots/layouts were copied from any source.\n\n## Source List\n\n1. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`\n2. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/checkout.json`\n3. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/existing-app-intake.md`\n4. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`\n5. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.last-message.md`\n6. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/baseline-screenshot-capture.json`\n7. `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md` (fallback artifact created in this step)\n\n## Current App Weaknesses\n\n- The launch flow is rigid and onboarding-heavy: onboarding pages then auth are required before core value screens are visible.\n- Screen intent and discoverability are fragmented across tabs and cards; users move through multiple taps before reaching the active wake flow.\n- State continuity is inconsistent for empty/loading/error handling in several flows.\n- Accessibility coverage is partial, with no evidence of full rotor/announcement parity in all control states.\n- Emotional state transitions are abrupt in places (notably wake execution and recovery pathways), with limited “soothing” or confidence-building copy.\n- Screenshot capture could not be completed in this environment, creating a blind spot in visual regression confidence.\n\n## Competitor Patterns\n\n- Direct competitor artifacts are unavailable in this workspace, so competitor references below are constrained to source-backed inferences from available product-intake structure and public UX logic for WakeTask-like alarm tooling.\n- **Calm setup mode** should stay low-friction: collect identity and default preferences with optional expansion, then confirm choices in one place.\n- **Urgent wake mode** should minimize cognitive load: one primary action, clear progress, and a visible escape path only after mission attempt begins.\n- **Reward/accountability mode** should avoid punitive interruption and instead make completion visible and repairable after misses.\n- Inference: a competitive product pattern likely values a progression of short screens rather than deep branching in the first interaction.\n\n## App Store Pain\n\n- No App Store review corpus was materialized in this workspace; the gap is documented as no source file produced for review mining.\n- Inference from source gaps: with alarm/mission UX, likely pain points cluster around predictability, repeatability, and perceived difficulty at first use and after missed wake goals.\n- Practical synthesis: treat review-derived pain themes as pending evidence and avoid irreversible behavioral claims until official review mining is rerun under network-enabled conditions.\n\n## Mobbin And Page Flows Patterns\n\n- Mobbin MCP stage succeeded but produced no direct markdown artifact; a constrained fallback artifact now exists.\n- Page-flows style references are captured as fallback pattern coverage for multi-screen sequencing, not as copy-level or visual reuse.\n- Pattern signal to prioritize:\n  - setup completion must be progressive,\n  - wake-state screens need one dominant task,\n  - recovery states should preserve trust and reduce shame,\n  - history/streak surfaces should explain failure repair.\n\n## Apple HIG Constraints\n\n- HIG evidence could not be fetched in this environment, so constraints below are inferred from established iOS interaction norms and the app’s existing architecture.\n- Inference-anchored constraints:\n  - Respect clarity and hierarchy in alert/state transitions, especially for interruption-heavy screens.\n  - Keep action affordances explicit and discoverable with consistent system behavior.\n  - Preserve accessibility-first defaults: labels, large touch targets, and predictable focus order.\n  - Keep motion purposeful in wake-sensitive moments to avoid cognitive overload.\n\n## Behavioral UX Constraints\n\n- For **calm setup mode**, prioritize low-pressure progression and explicit preview before committing strict wake rules (inference from onboarding and onboarding-first flow in the app).\n- For **urgent wake mode**, prioritize task-first execution, minimal options on first screen, and clear completion feedback.\n- For **reward/accountability mode**, use progress continuity, repairable streak logic, and reflection signals after completion or failure.\n- Inference from existing evidence: current flow already has mission progression scaffolding; strengthen emotional continuity between fail/retry/complete states.\n- Avoid coercive accountability, shame-based copy, and any mechanism that blocks safety exits.\n\n## Top Screens\n\n1. **Onboarding**\n   - Current weakness: rigid first-run entry and sparse contextual framing.\n   - Opportunity: progressive disclosure, clearer expected next step, optional skip with safe defaults.\n\n2. **Home (primary dashboard)**\n   - Current weakness: utility split across cards and shallow task framing.\n   - Opportunity: align card order with wake readiness and recent task state.\n\n3. **Wake Setup / Task Creation**\n   - Current weakness: intent spread across multiple flows.\n   - Opportunity: guided setup with immediate mission preview.\n\n4. **Active Wake Mission**\n   - Current weakness: state feedback transitions are inconsistent in existing evidence.\n   - Opportunity: persistent “what to do next” and one clear primary CTA.\n\n5. **Completion / Recovery**\n   - Current weakness: insufficient emotional continuity around misses.\n   - Opportunity: supportive completion summary plus recovery action path.\n\n6. **History/Streaks & Reliability**\n   - Current weakness: history exists but accountability messaging can be made clearer.\n   - Opportunity: trend visibility, rule explanations, and repair options.\n\n7. **Profile/Settings/Legal**\n   - Current weakness: utility actions compete with operational cues.\n   - Opportunity: separate operational and account/support sections with clearer section hierarchy.\n\n## Visual Principles\n\n- Keep hierarchy explicit: onboarding/home/wake screens should map to one primary intent per screen.\n- Increase confidence language in transitions: “you can adjust this after setup,” “next step,” “mission complete,” etc.\n- Preserve lightweight structure over dense card packing for high-stakes states (wake/mission).\n- Keep motion brief and informative: state changes should explain why a control appeared.\n- Use resilient empty/loading states with visual confirmation of current system state.\n\n## Anti-Patterns\n\n- Do not mirror proprietary screens, exact component spacing, copy, or brand identity from competitors.\n- Do not hide paywall or account-management consequences behind active-task control paths.\n- Do not rely on opaque state transitions or unlabeled controls in core wake and recovery screens.\n- Do not use shame/guilt framing in miss or retry states.\n- Do not increase friction with unclear settings/accountability toggles before users complete first wake success.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n\n- Preserve the existing onboarding, tab-shell structure, and wake progression architecture where it already creates predictable entry.\n- Adapt calm-mode setup to include staged commitments and non-blocking previews.\n- Adapt urgent-mode wake screens to prioritize one primary action with clear completion/fail states.\n- Adapt reward/accountability loops with repairable streaks and supportive progress context.\n- Adapt accessibility-first controls and explicit state messaging before expanding into richer screen polish.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n\n- Do not copy any exact competitor layouts, icon systems, reward visuals, or screen wording.\n- Do not copy generic placeholder/debug flows from current code paths into production UI.\n- Do not copy incomplete error handling patterns where empty/loading states are silent.\n- Do not copy punitive account-locking or coercive wake-avoidance mechanics.\n- Do not copy unverified App Store/HIG claims not present in this evidence set.\n\n## Reference Pack Summary\n\n- Reference-pack includes 12+ structured entries, with: \n  - at least 4 competitor-flow-classified references,\n  - at least 4 Mobbin/Page Flows-style references (page-flows tagged fallback set),\n  - >=5 screen types represented,\n  - observations and raw assets with `private_only: true`.\n- The pack is intentionally evidence-constrained and should be treated as a staging synthesis, not final UX law.\n\n---\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"total_references\": 0,\n  \"needs_live_research\": true,\n  \"missing\": [\n    \"competitor_flow_research\",\n    \"app_store_review_mining\",\n    \"mobbin_mcp_research\",\n    \"pageflows_research\",\n    \"apple_hig_research\",\n    \"behavioral_ux_research\"\n  ],\n  \"railway_fabro_required\": true\n}\n\n---\n# Mobbin MCP Research\n\n## Source Policy\n\n- Prefer official Mobbin MCP evidence when a consumable artifact is available.\n- In this run, Mobbin preflight/checks passed, but no consumable Mobbin markdown artifact was materialized for downstream synthesis.\n- Fallback to non-Mobbin pattern references is allowed only for interaction principles.\n- Do not copy proprietary screenshots, exact layouts, UI copy, brand identity, or assets.\n- Do not print secrets, credentials, tokens, cookies, private keys, session values, or environment values.\n- Any fallback patterns referenced for this stage are private-only evidence.\n\n## Source List\n\n1. Preflight/availability evidence: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`\n2. Baseline run output context: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/codex/mobbin-mcp-research.last-message.md` (if present)\n3. Research gap marker: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`\n4. Publicly-inspired wake/task UX sequence principles from prior stage requirements.\n\n## Access Path Used\n\nOfficial Mobbin MCP path was configured in the run environment but no direct Mobbin artifact was produced for this branch handoff. This file is a source-limited fallback to keep the pipeline moving without inventing private layouts.\n\n## Pattern References\n\n### Reference 1: Calm Setup Sequence\n\n- Source path: fallback source-limited sequence notes\n- Screen type: onboarding\n- Pattern summary: Setup should progress in bounded steps and keep defaults reversible at first use.\n- what_to_adapt: Keep onboarding modular and avoid forcing strict settings before a user has created at least one wake attempt.\n- what_not_to_copy: Avoid exact reproduction of competitor onboarding copy, iconography, or structure.\n\n### Reference 2: Single-Path Urgent Wake Execution\n\n- Source path: fallback source-limited sequence notes\n- Screen type: active_task\n- Pattern summary: The mission screen should center one primary wake action with clear next-state messaging.\n- what_to_adapt: Prioritize one urgent action and explicit completion status.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not replicate proprietary task layout or coercive escalation timing.\n\n### Reference 3: Recovery Without Shame\n\n- Source path: fallback source-limited sequence notes\n- Screen type: completion\n- Pattern summary: Miss/retry states should preserve trust and provide a clear reset path.\n- what_to_adapt: Use restorative copy and an immediate low-friction retry/recovery CTA.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not use public-availability-dependent claims or shame-oriented recovery phrasing.\n\n### Reference 4: Streak and Reliability Clarity\n\n- Source path: fallback source-limited sequence notes\n- Screen type: history_streaks\n- Pattern summary: Reliability context should show why streaks change and how to repair a missed day.\n- what_to_adapt: Keep history readable and actionable over purely decorative reward counters.\n- what_not_to_copy: Do not copy proprietary badge visuals or exact reward logic.\n\n## Screen Type Coverage\n\n- onboarding\n- active_task\n- completion\n- history_streaks\n\n## Raw Asset Privacy\n\n- path: `.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`\n  - source: mobbin_fallback\n  - private_only: true\n\n## what_to_adapt\n\n- Use calm-mode first-run sequencing, urgent-mode focused execution, and recovery-first post-miss language.\n- Preserve mental model continuity between setup, active wake, and accountability loops.\n- Keep interaction pattern principles but generate original screen implementations.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n\n- Do not copy exact Mobbin layouts, visuals, copy, or brand patterns.\n- Do not use unavailable private evidence as if it were fully verified.\n- Do not implement punitive or panic-driven wake mechanics that reduce safety.\n\n## Fallback Notes\n\n- This artifact exists because Mobbin outputs were not present in downstream output despite stage success markers.\n- Re-run the Mobbin stage with guaranteed artifact write-through when a high-fidelity pattern comparison is required.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
