{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_17","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat <<'EOF' > /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md\n# App Store Review Mining\n\n## Source Policy\n- Used only public App Store listing pages, public ratings pages, and visible App Store review snippets.\n- Sources are from storefront \"'`us` and the same App Store URL space (`apps.apple.com`).\n- No app screenshots, proprietary layouts, or private data were collected.\n- Private user detail was not copied; review details are paraphrased where needed.\n- App names and storefront info are treated as public metadata only.\n\n## Source List\n- App Store listings and reviews for Alarmy, ProAlarm, SleepTown, Orlo, CarpeDiem, and TickTick.\n- App Store listing and reviews for Habitica.\n- URLs:\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/alarmy-loud-alarm-clock/id1163786766?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/proalarm-mission-alarm-clock/id6599855565?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/sleeptown/id1210251567?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/sleeptown/id1210251567`\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/orlo-alarm-wake-up-challenge/id6760335025`\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/carpediem-alarm-motivation/id6739722555`\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/carpediem-alarm-motivation/id6739722555?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/ticktick-to-do-list-calendar/id626144601?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n  - `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/habitica-gamified-taskmanager/id994882113?see-all=reviews`\n\n## Apps And Review Sources\n\n| App | Storefront | Source URL | Review date range | Evidence quality |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Alarmy – Loud alarm clock | US (`us`) | App Store listing + ratings | 2021-2025 (visible snippets) | High (large catalog, multiple recent reviews) |\n| ProAlarm: Mission Alarm Clock | US (`us`) | Ratings page | 2025 | Medium (very low volume; repeated same complaint) |\n| SleepTown | US (`us`) | Ratings page | 2020-2025 | Medium (small review sample, mostly mixed sentiment) |\n| Orlo Alarm: Wake Up Challenge | US (`us`) | Listing + ratings snippet | 2026 (month-level visible in snippet) | Low (single-review pattern, small sample) |\n| CarpeDiem: Alarm Motivation | US (`us`) | Listing + ratings page | 2025 | Medium (low-mid volume with explicit usability/reliability comments) |\n| TickTick: To-Do List & Calendar | US (`us`) | Ratings page + listing | 2025-present visible snippet | High (large catalog and diverse feature feedback) |\n| Habitica: Gamified Taskmanager | US (`us`) | Ratings page + listing | 2020-present visible sample | Medium (older reviews, mix of support and feature mentions) |\n\n## Complaint Themes\n\n1. **Alarm reliability is the top failure mode across mission-based wake apps.** Reviews repeatedly mention alarms not firing when the app is closed or when system conditions change.\n2. **Mission execution friction can be excessive or inconsistent.** Users report movement missions feeling too sensitive or too hard to complete reliably.\n3. **Background / system-limitability confusion.** Multiple apps trigger trust drops when reviewers complain the app cannot reliably ring under certain device states.\n4. **Pricing and value-pressure risk.** Premium paywalls are often viewed as expensive for users who need accountability features most.\n5. **In-app behavioral tone can undermine trust.** Some users find unusual “motivational” text or strictness patterns unsettling, especially early morning.\n6. **Feature promises can be inconsistent with implementation.** Reviews note mismatches between mission descriptions and how strict or forgiving execution feels in reality.\n\n## Praise Themes\n\n1. **Mission-first wake flow is valued when it reliably forces physical/mental activation.** Reviewers repeatedly say it helps them stop hitting snooze.\n2. **Simple and fast wake completion flow increases trust.** App sections with one clear objective before alarm dismissal get repeated praise.\n3. **Progress and streak context strengthens commitment.** Users respond well to visible history/building or consistency incentives.\n4. **Task consolidation and reminders matter for cognitive load.** In task management reviews, people praise a clean “one place” mental model for urgent and recurring tasks.\n5. **Clear upgrade boundaries reduce churn concern when honest.** Calm, direct upgrade language and transparent feature boundaries correlate with better review quality than vague upsell pressure.\n\n## Feature Requests\n\n- More robust mission options, especially with adjustable intensity, accessible alternatives, and less error-prone movement detection.\n- Better “first-run safety behavior”: clear warning states for background limitations and why an alarm did not fire.\n- Optional morning messaging and coaching controls so users can disable or tone down notifications.\n- Longer-term value for premium users via stable reliability improvements rather than extra coercive gating.\n- Better recovery and skip paths after mission failure so users do not feel punished for missed wake-ups.\n\n## Retention And Churn Signals\n\n- **Retention-positive:** mission-based wake-ups that reliably create a predictable routine (high praise for “actually gets me out of bed”).\n- **Churn-risk:** repeated reliability complaints about non-firing alarms and strictness with low tolerance for false failures.\n- **Monetization churn-risk:** reviews mention unexpected subscription friction and premium cost burden after free period.\n- **Support signal:** proactive developer responses are present in some apps and help reduce rage when reliability issues are framed as OS/platform constraints.\n- **Trust signal:** very low-review-volume apps with hard claims should be treated as fragile references for UX decisions; avoid copying exact flow if evidence quality is weak.\n\n## Screen Type Implications\n\n- **onboarding**: explain platform constraints early (especially background limitations), avoid promising behavior that iOS can’t guarantee.\n- **home**: prioritize clarity of next action over dense card noise, and show today’s wake objective and next accountability step.\n- **create_edit**: expose mission intensity and skip options clearly so first setup is low friction and adaptable.\n- **active_task**: keep one dominant action per screen; avoid competing controls in wake-critical moments.\n- **completion**: provide explicit recovery and success language rather than shame; include what to do next immediately.\n- **history_streaks**: keep history useful without punitive messaging; clarify why streaks changed.\n- **profile_settings**: include transparent subscription controls and clear interruption-risk settings.\n- **paywall_subscription**: keep upgrade prompts contextual and optional; avoid interruptive upsell during critical wake attempt paths.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n\n- Keep mission-based wake structure, but preserve a clear fallback path when mission execution fails.\n- Add explicit reliability education in onboarding and when alarms are disabled by background/OS conditions.\n- Offer adjustable mission intensity and accessibility-first alternatives for physical/brain tasks.\n- Tie progression to a simple, positive streak model with repair actions, not just penalties.\n- Make paywall language explicit: what is disabled, what is preview-only, and how to continue as a free user.\n- Preserve concise onboarding copy and keep the onboarding-to-setup transition fast.\n- Include explicit confirmation states in active-run screen (mission in progress, waiting, failed, completed).\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n\n- Do not copy aggressive unlock patterns that force users into premium before first meaningful success.\n- Do not overuse personality-heavy motivational messaging that can be interpreted as intrusive or tone-deaf.\n- Do not copy vague mission-activation claims when actual behavior depends on OS state.\n- Do not replicate micro-friction loops with too many mission taps at wake time.\n- Do not ship “anti-uninstall” or similarly coercive mechanisms that reduce trust.\n\n## Reference Entries\n\n### Entry 1\n- **App name:** Alarmy – Loud alarm clock\n- **Review theme:** Reliability and mission effectiveness\n- **Affected screen type:** active_task, completion\n- **Evidence summary:** Review corpus indicates users appreciate mission-based wake-up reliability and loud escalation, but also report background-dependency and sensitivity issues in movement missions.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Use alarm-and-task flow that is straightforward and effective once mission starts; provide clear failure fallback.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Avoid assuming every mission will reliably fire in all system states without warning states.\n\n### Entry 2\n- **App name:** Alarmy – Loud alarm clock\n- **Review theme:** Pricing sensitivity and trust around premium value\n- **Affected screen type:** paywall_subscription, profile_settings\n- **Evidence summary:** Reviews include concerns about subscription cost and barriers for users who need stronger wake accountability the most.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Keep upgrade costs and benefits explicit at onboarding and during settings transitions.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Avoid hard “must-pay for core wake function” patterns.\n\n### Entry 3\n- **App name:** Alarmy – Loud alarm clock\n- **Review theme:** Emotional tone in post-wake interactions\n- **Affected screen type:** completion\n- **Evidence summary:** Some users call motivational post-alarm messaging unsettling and confusing.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Keep completion messages short, predictable, and user-controlled.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Avoid tone-heavy AI/voice nudges that can trigger negative emotional reactions.\n\n### Entry 4\n- **App name:** ProAlarm: Mission Alarm Clock\n- **Review theme:** Alarms not ringing when app is closed\n- **Affected screen type:** active_task\n- **Evidence summary:** Multiple 2025 reviews specifically flag missed alarms when app is force-closed; developer repeatedly cites OS restrictions.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Add pre-run system-status checks, explicit warning copy, and safer alarm readiness states.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Do not hide system constraints behind generic “fixing issue” language.\n\n### Entry 5\n- **App name:** SleepTown\n- **Review theme:** Streak-based motivation and strict-mode pain\n- **Affected screen type:** history_streaks, completion\n- **Evidence summary:** Positive streak feedback is tied to visible motivation; negative feedback highlights strict-mode failure frustration and reset pain.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Keep consistency incentives and give forgiving recovery options.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Do not make streak loss feel like punishment with no path to recovery.\n\n### Entry 6\n- **App name:** Orlo Alarm\n- **Review theme:** Mission variety and anti-snooze behavior\n- **Affected screen type:** active_task\n- **Evidence summary:** Small-sample reviews praise task-before-dismiss mechanics and daily discipline outcomes.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Preserve fast mission completion patterns and “single mission unlocks alarm off” clarity.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Avoid high-volume upsell language and under-sampled feature assumptions in onboarding.\n\n### Entry 7\n- **App name:** CarpeDiem: Alarm Motivation\n- **Review theme:** Reliability + billing friction\n- **Affected screen type:** active_task, paywall_subscription\n- **Evidence summary:** Some users report the app helping wake-up behavior, while others complain the alarm did not go off and that billing confusion persisted after free period.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Pair reliability-first defaults with explicit troubleshooting tips and clear cancellation path.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Avoid stacking mission promises with brittle “always works” positioning.\n\n### Entry 8\n- **App name:** TickTick: To-Do List & Calendar\n- **Review theme:** Task capture, reminders, and reduced cognitive load\n- **Affected screen type:** create_edit, home\n- **Evidence summary:** High-volume reviews praise organization, reminders, and single-view control of tasks; less direct wake-specific behavior.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Borrow clean task-entry and checklist mental model for WakeTask first-run flow.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Do not import excessive feature density from generic task apps into mission-critical wake screens.\n\n### Entry 9\n- **App name:** Habitica: Gamified Taskmanager\n- **Review theme:** Engagement through habit gamification and community signals\n- **Affected screen type:** history_streaks, home\n- **Evidence summary:** Positive reviews value motivational task framing; occasional feature bug reports indicate inventory/feedback reliability matters.\n- **what_to_adapt:** Use lightweight accountability reinforcement and visible progression.\n- **what_not_to_copy:** Avoid complex RPG-style mechanics that distract from wake-critical simplicity.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
