{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_20","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"mkdir -p /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRSF5GBPG07T76DS9X1PJX8S/parallel/research_fanout/app_store_review_mining/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research && cat <<'EOF' > /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRSF5GBPG07T76DS9X1PJX8S/parallel/research_fanout/app_store_review_mining/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md\n# App Store Review Mining\n\n## Source Policy\n- Used only public App Store listing pages, public ratings pages, and visible App Store review snippets.\n- Sources are from storefront \"'`us` and `https://apps.apple.com/`.\n- No private user data, tokens, or credentials were collected.\n- Sensitive personal text was summarized instead of copied verbatim.\n- No proprietary screenshots, exact UI copy, or brand assets were reused.\n\n## Source List\n- Alarmy listing and review page: `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/alarmy-loud-alarm-clock/id1163786766?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n- ProAlarm listing and review page: `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/proalarm-mission-alarm-clock/id6599855565?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n- SleepTown listing and review page: `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/sleeptown/id1210251567?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n- Orlo listing and reviews: `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/orlo-alarm-wake-up-challenge/id6760335025`\n- CarpeDiem listing and review page: `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/carpediem-alarm-motivation/id6739722555?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n- TickTick listing and review page: `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/ticktick-to-do-list-calendar/id626144601?platform=iphone&see-all=reviews`\n- Habitica listing and review page: `https://apps.apple.com/us/app/habitica-gamified-taskmanager/id994882113?see-all=reviews`\n\n## Apps And Review Sources\n\n1. **Alarmy – Loud alarm clock (US / `us`)**\n   - Source URL: `apps.apple.com/us/app/alarmy-loud-alarm-clock/...`\n   - Review date range found: 2021–2025\n   - Evidence quality: High (large sample of ratings plus review snippets with dates)\n\n2. **ProAlarm: Mission Alarm Clock (US / `us`)**\n   - Source URL: `apps.apple.com/us/app/proalarm-mission-alarm-clock/...`\n   - Review date range found: 2025\n   - Evidence quality: Medium (low sample size, repetitive issue pattern)\n\n3. **SleepTown (US / `us`)**\n   - Source URL: `apps.apple.com/us/app/sleeptown/...`\n   - Review date range found: 2020–2025 visible snippets\n   - Evidence quality: Medium (moderate volume, mixed sentiment)\n\n4. **Orlo Alarm: Wake Up Challenge (US / `us`)**\n   - Source URL: `apps.apple.com/us/app/orlo-alarm-wake-up-challenge/...`\n   - Review date range found: 2026 (month-level snippets)\n   - Evidence quality: Low (very small review volume)\n\n5. **CarpeDiem: Alarm Motivation (US / `us`)**\n   - Source URL: `apps.apple.com/us/app/carpediem-alarm-motivation/...`\n   - Review date range found: 2025\n   - Evidence quality: Medium (small sample, clear opposing sentiments)\n\n6. **TickTick: To-Do List & Calendar (US / `us`)**\n   - Source URL: `apps.apple.com/us/app/ticktick-to-do-list-calendar/...`\n   - Review date range found: 2025\n   - Evidence quality: High (large catalog with practical workflow feedback)\n\n7. **Habitica: Gamified Taskmanager (US / `us`)**\n   - Source URL: `apps.apple.com/us/app/habitica-gamified-taskmanager/...`\n   - Review date range found: 2020 and later\n   - Evidence quality: Medium (older corpus, still relevant engagement patterns)\n\n## Complaint Themes\n\n1. **Reliability risk when app is backgrounded/closed**\n   - Alarming repeatedly appears to stop or fail when app lifecycle state changes.\n   - Review pattern is strongest in mission alarm apps.\n\n2. **Mission friction and false failures**\n   - Movement missions and verification steps can feel hard or overly sensitive, creating extra cognitive and physical overhead.\n\n3. **Monetization friction and perceived fairness**\n   - Reviewers mention trial-to-paid transitions, value anxiety, and premium expectations that do not match outcomes.\n\n4. **Trust and tone mismatch in motivational messaging**\n   - Morning message behavior can trigger discomfort when tone feels random or intrusive.\n\n5. **Complexity leakage into wake-critical moments**\n   - Too many settings and branching choices in active wake moments reduce confidence and increase chance of giving up.\n\n## Praise Themes\n\n1. **Mission-first wake model works for hard-to-wake users**\n   - Many reviewers credit challenge-based missions for breaking snooze loops.\n\n2. **Progress loops improve consistency**\n   - Streaks/history mechanics feel motivating when they are understandable and forgiving.\n\n3. **Clean task list structures reduce cognitive load**\n   - TickTick-style task centralization and reminders are praised for mental clarity.\n\n4. **Positive reinforcement from small completions**\n   - Completion states described as motivating when predictable and non-shaming.\n\n## Feature Requests\n\n- Make alarm reliability status explicit before users rely on the app at critical moments.\n- Add mission personalization controls (difficulty, type, accessibility alternatives).\n- Improve recovery after failed wake attempts (grace, retry, and reset flow).\n- Reduce surprise and increase clarity around trial/subscription boundaries.\n- Keep copy transparent and less personality-heavy in critical wake moments.\n\n## Retention And Churn Signals\n\n- **Retention supports:** mission efficacy, clear progress, and simple day-start routines.\n- **Retention risks:** reliability failures and perceived lock-in reduce trust quickly.\n- **Churn accelerants:** unclear paywall pressure and inconsistent mission behavior.\n- **Protective signal:** explicit platform-limitation messaging in review responses appears to reduce frustration.\n\n## Screen Type Implications\n\n- **onboarding:** set expectations for alarm/background behavior, required permissions, and realistic mission outcomes.\n- **home:** prioritize one-screen clarity: today’s wake objective, next task, and status.\n- **primary_list:** keep task list discoverability strong but avoid overloading with unnecessary task-management features.\n- **create_edit:** simplify mission selection, defaults, and required-time setup.\n- **active_task:** one dominant action + visible state progress while alarm task is active.\n- **completion:** emotional reset and next-step recovery must be clear and immediate.\n- **history_streaks:** explain what changes streaks and how users can recover from misses.\n- **profile_settings:** surfaced subscription/account transparency and reliability help controls.\n- **paywall_subscription:** context-sensitive upsell only after value is demonstrated.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n\n- Keep mission-driven wake as the core value proposition, with visible primary action and no extra branching at wake time.\n- Use explicit system-status labels where background/permission constraints may affect behavior.\n- Build a recoverable miss flow that lets users recover confidence after failure.\n- Add transparent paywall boundaries and minimal, plain-language upgrade language.\n- Preserve concise progress feedback over novelty effects in critical screens.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n\n- Do not replicate opaque alarm behavior that appears unreliable with no explicit status.\n- Do not overload active wake screens with many mission options or ambiguous controls.\n- Do not mimic invasive or eerie motivational messaging patterns.\n- Do not use strict “anti-uninstall / coercive” mechanics that reduce trust.\n- Do not copy task-app UI density into time-critical wake execution screens.\n\n## Reference Entries\n\n- **App:** Alarmy – Loud alarm clock\n  - **Review theme:** reliability + mission friction + tone in messaging\n  - **Affected screen type:** active_task, completion\n  - **Evidence summary:** High-volume reviews praise mission efficacy; some reviews criticize unreliability when app is not running and odd motivational tone.\n  - **what_to_adapt:** Keep wake mission effectiveness with clearer failure/fallback states.\n  - **what_not_to_copy:** Do not present alarms as uniformly reliable without system caveats.\n\n- **App:** ProAlarm: Mission Alarm Clock\n  - **Review theme:** non-firing alarm behavior under app-close conditions\n  - **Affected screen type:** active_task\n  - **Evidence summary:** Multiple recent US reviews report missed rings when app is closed; developer acknowledges OS restrictions.\n  - **what_to_adapt:** add warning states, readiness checks, and transparent readiness instructions.\n  - **what_not_to_copy:** do not hide background limitations and blame users without guidance.\n\n- **App:** SleepTown\n  - **Review theme:** consistency motivation vs strictness pain\n  - **Affected screen type:** history_streaks, completion\n  - **Evidence summary:** Streak/game mechanics help routine adherence, but users dislike unrecoverable “broken” outcomes.\n  - **what_to_adapt:** maintain visible progress with gentle reset paths.\n  - **what_not_to_copy:** do not penalize misses with irreversible-seeming punishments.\n\n- **App:** Orlo Alarm: Wake Up Challenge\n  - **Review theme:** direct task-before-dismiss engagement\n  - **Affected screen type:** active_task\n  - **Evidence summary:** Small-sample praise focuses on one-screen challenge completion and immediate wake benefits.\n  - **what_to_adapt:** keep mission execution simple and immediate.\n  - **what_not_to_copy:** do not over-generalize from very low review volume.\n\n- **App:** CarpeDiem: Alarm Motivation\n  - **Review theme:** practical tasks with mixed reliability and billing feedback\n  - **Affected screen type:** active_task, paywall_subscription\n  - **Evidence summary:** Some users validate mission utility; others report missed alarms and billing confusion.\n  - **what_to_adapt:** pair motivation with stronger reliability defaults and transparent billing UX.\n  - **what_not_to_copy:** do not promise motivation depth if reliability is unstable.\n\n- **App:** TickTick: To-Do List & Calendar\n  - **Review theme:** organization and task completion clarity\n  - **Affected screen type:** primary_list, create_edit, home\n  - **Evidence summary:** large sample praises fast task capture, reminders, and unified workflows.\n  - **what_to_adapt:** adopt concise task-entry model and clear weekly/monthly visibility.\n  - **what_not_to_copy:** avoid transporting every feature affordance into wake-critical paths.\n\n- **App:** Habitica: Gamified Taskmanager\n  - **Review theme:** sustained engagement through progression systems\n  - **Affected screen type:** history_streaks, home\n  - **Evidence summary:** reviewers credit gamified/task framing with sustained attention; also mention occasional feature bugs.\n  - **what_to_adapt:** use lightweight streak-reward language and social accountability cues.\n  - **what_not_to_copy:** avoid complex RPG mechanics and dependency-heavy progression layers in core wake flow.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
